programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they try to design and construct the home of their dreams. Ariane Prevost, an architect at the pinnacle her career, plans to ditch the drafting desk, don steel-capped boots and take up a blowtorch as the antidote to a lifetime of designing houses for other people. With three adult children, Ariane and her husband Neil are ready to downsize and they've found the ideal plot in the conservative Perth suburb of Claremont. Ariane is taking on a trilogy of tasks: architect, client and builder, and with no one to answer to but herself, her plan is to make it up as she goes along. She's a force to be reckoned with, on site very morning at 5am, making breakfast for her co-builders, wielding tools with tradesmen and designing as she goes. But beneath her free-wheeling attitude, Ariane has a serious mandate: to create a home that blurs the lines between inside and out, with seamless living and outdoor areas, flexible sleeping quarters and a multi-use rooftop space. Her methods are as unconventional as many of her materials and her quirks are peppered throughout the house, including an 'origami' showpiece sitting on top. Can Ariane pull off the construction of this unusual home and survive the gruelling 70-hour weeks she's putting in to get it done?(n)

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Brand new series: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they try to design and construct the home of their dreams. When civil engineer Joe Cato and his wife Maura made the decision to sell their construction business and spend more time with their grown-up children, they were partly driven by the chance find of some land at Foxground, near Kiama on the south coast of New South Wales: 80 acres that included their own rainforest. They soon hatched a plan to turn Foxground into their permanent home, with a strong agenda to tread as lightly on the planet as possible, live completely off-grid and build using a material known for its low embodied energy and natural ability to preserve heat - rammed earth. But it's only as they embark on the process that they realise the complexities of the challenge ahead. Refining the mix correctly for the rammed earth so it doesn't collapse is only the beginning. As their journey progresses, it dawns on them that there may be one fundamental problem with their entire design, and that one of their chosen material's greatest merits, its ability to store heat, might now turn into their biggest issue. It could end up sucking heat out of the house, making it completely inefficient. And, with 80 rammed-earth panels in a solar-powered, south-facing house, that's a very real concern(n)

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they try to design and construct the home of their dreams. Melbourne doctors Ian Kronborg and Ann Howard are driven to create a home like no other. Their plan is to build a three-storey house clad entirely with water tanks: massive, two-metre-high, H-shaped black plastic beasts that will form the skin of their new abode. The 30-odd tanks necessary to cover the house will hold over 50,000 litres of water - enough to cover their needs for a lifetime and irrigate a rooftop garden too. Ian also has plans for living green walls, with vertical gardens and hanging foliage that should drape the exterior in years to come. It's a design that's bound to get the neighbours talking in a suburb brimming with tiny, traditional, weatherboard single-fronted workers' cottages. After two years chasing planning approval, and then losing their builder, Ian and Ann find they are delayed once more when the council deems that a power pole is too close to the house. It would be enough to make most couples give up, but Ian and Ann push on, each with their own individualistic view of what this house will be. While Ian is focused on the sustainable qualities and operations of the water tank concept, Ann has the more romantic aim of creating a light-filled environment reminiscent of an Italian villa. Can their two ideals meet?(n)

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they try to design and construct the home of their dreams. Ariane Prevost, an architect at the pinnacle her career, plans to ditch the drafting desk, don steel-capped boots and take up a blowtorch as the antidote to a lifetime of designing houses for other people. With three adult children, Ariane and her husband Neil are ready to downsize and they've found the ideal plot in the conservative Perth suburb of Claremont. Ariane is taking on a trilogy of tasks: architect, client and builder, and with no one to answer to but herself, her plan is to make it up as she goes along. She's a force to be reckoned with, on site very morning at 5am, making breakfast for her co-builders, wielding tools with tradesmen and designing as she goes. But beneath her free-wheeling attitude, Ariane has a serious mandate: to create a home that blurs the lines between inside and out, with seamless living and outdoor areas, flexible sleeping quarters and a multi-use rooftop space. Her methods are as unconventional as many of her materials and her quirks are peppered throughout the house, including an 'origami' showpiece sitting on top. Can Ariane pull off the construction of this unusual home and survive the gruelling 70-hour weeks she's putting in to get it done?(n)

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Brand new series: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they try to design and construct the home of their dreams. When civil engineer Joe Cato and his wife Maura made the decision to sell their construction business and spend more time with their grown-up children, they were partly driven by the chance find of some land at Foxground, near Kiama on the south coast of New South Wales: 80 acres that included their own rainforest. They soon hatched a plan to turn Foxground into their permanent home, with a strong agenda to tread as lightly on the planet as possible, live completely off-grid and build using a material known for its low embodied energy and natural ability to preserve heat - rammed earth. But it's only as they embark on the process that they realise the complexities of the challenge ahead. Refining the mix correctly for the rammed earth so it doesn't collapse is only the beginning. As their journey progresses, it dawns on them that there may be one fundamental problem with their entire design, and that one of their chosen material's greatest merits, its ability to store heat, might now turn into their biggest issue. It could end up sucking heat out of the house, making it completely inefficient. And, with 80 rammed-earth panels in a solar-powered, south-facing house, that's a very real concern(n)

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they try to design and construct the home of their dreams. Melbourne doctors Ian Kronborg and Ann Howard are driven to create a home like no other. Their plan is to build a three-storey house clad entirely with water tanks: massive, two-metre-high, H-shaped black plastic beasts that will form the skin of their new abode. The 30-odd tanks necessary to cover the house will hold over 50,000 litres of water - enough to cover their needs for a lifetime and irrigate a rooftop garden too. Ian also has plans for living green walls, with vertical gardens and hanging foliage that should drape the exterior in years to come. It's a design that's bound to get the neighbours talking in a suburb brimming with tiny, traditional, weatherboard single-fronted workers' cottages. After two years chasing planning approval, and then losing their builder, Ian and Ann find they are delayed once more when the council deems that a power pole is too close to the house. It would be enough to make most couples give up, but Ian and Ann push on, each with their own individualistic view of what this house will be. While Ian is focused on the sustainable qualities and operations of the water tank concept, Ann has the more romantic aim of creating a light-filled environment reminiscent of an Italian villa. Can their two ideals meet?(n)
